    {
      "turn_number": 28,
      "role": "persona",
      "type": "response",
      "text": "I guess I keep coming back to the little moments — the positive test in my bathroom, the way my boyfriend squeezed my hand and laughed like it was the best surprise, then the quiet panic when I looked at my bank account. I want to be honest with providers, to say “I’m scared about money and hours and being judged,” and have them listen without lecturing. Today the doctor said everything looks low risk and I should feel lucky, but I also left feeling like a number in a schedule.\n\nPractical stuff matters so much: later appointments, help with bus or clinic vouchers, clear explanations so I don’t feel lost, and someone to answer questions without making me feel silly. I also want excitement acknowledged — not just checkboxes. Little things like a nurse who remembers my name, or a clinician who asks about how we’re planning for childcare and work, make a huge difference.\n\nI’m trying to advocate for myself, but some days I’m exhausted from anxiety about money and work and wondering if I’ll lose my footing. Still, I hold onto hope — for a healthy baby, for a supportive team, for help that feels human, not transactional.",
      "responding_to_question_id": "Q13",
      "input_tokens": 1292,
      "output_tokens": 500
    },
